  "output": "## Test Coverage Analysis — jobsquare\n\n**Current state: 0% coverage.** No `tests/` directory, no pytest config, no test dependencies in `requirements.txt`, and no test files anywhere in the ~1500-line codebase (`agent.py`, `cli.py`, `fetchers.py`, `filters.py`, `models.py`, `notify.py`, `pipeline.py`, `store.py`). Every function below is currently untested.\n\n### Suggested setup (add once, first PR)\n```\n# requirements-dev.txt\npytest>=8.0\npytest-asyncio>=0.24\nrespx>=0.21          # mock httpx transport for fetcher tests\nfreezegun>=1.5        # freeze datetime.now() for posted_at / cutoff tests\n```\n```ini\n# pytest.ini\n[pytest]\nasyncio_mode = auto\n```\n\n---\n\n## 1. `models.py` — pure logic, highest ROI, zero cost to test\n\n**Untested:** `parse_posted_at`, `Job.key`, `Job.posted_dt`, `Job.content_hash`, `Job.to_row`\n\n**Gaps:**\n- Epoch-seconds vs epoch-milliseconds boundary (`999_999_999_999` vs `1_000_000_000_000`)\n- Negative epoch strings (`\"-5\"` passes `lstrip(\"-\").isdigit()`)\n- ISO string without `Z`/offset (naive) — must become UTC-aware\n- ISO string with `Z`\n- Empty string, `None`-like, garbage string (`\"Posted 3 Days Ago\"` from Workday) → `None`\n- `content_hash` stability/uniqueness — same inputs → same hash, changed title/loc/url/department → different hash, but **unchanged fields not in the hash** (e.g. `posted_at`, `salary_range`) should NOT change it\n- `to_row` drops `raw`, adds `key`/`content_hash`\n\n```python\n# tests/test_models.py\nimport pytest\nfrom datetime import timezone\nfrom models import Job, parse_posted_at\n\nclass TestParsePostedAt:\n    def test_empty_returns_none(self):\n        assert parse_posted_at(\"\") is None\n\n    def test_epoch_milliseconds(self):\n        dt = parse_posted_at(\"1643241332430\")\n        assert dt.tzinfo == timezone.utc\n        assert dt.year == 2022\n\n    def test_epoch_seconds(self):\n        dt = parse_posted_at(\"1643241332\")\n        assert dt.year == 2022\n\n    def test_iso_with_z_suffix(self):\n        dt = parse_posted_at(\"2026-01-01T00:00:00Z\")\n        assert dt.tzinfo == timezone.utc\n\n    def test_iso_naive_gets_utc_attached(self):\n        dt = parse_posted_at(\"2026-01-01T00:00:00\")\n        assert dt.tzinfo == timezone.utc\n\n    def test_unparseable_prose_returns_none(self):\n        assert parse_posted_at(\"Posted 3 Days Ago\") is None\n\n    def test_negative_numeric_string(self):\n        # currently: lstrip(\"-\").isdigit() is True -> treated as epoch\n        assert parse_posted_at(\"-100\") is not None\n\n\nclass TestJob:\n    def _job(self, **kw):\n        base = dict(source=\"greenhouse\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\",\n                    title=\"Engineer\", url=\"https://x/1\")\n        base.update(kw)\n        return Job(**base)\n\n    def test_key_format(self):\n        assert self._job().key == \"greenhouse:acme:1\"\n\n    def test_content_hash_changes_on_title(self):\n        a, b = self._job(), self._job(title=\"Senior Engineer\")\n        assert a.content_hash != b.content_hash\n\n    def test_content_hash_stable_on_salary_or_posted_at_change(self):\n        a = self._job()\n        b = self._job(salary_range=\"$100k\", posted_at=\"2026-01-01\")\n        assert a.content_hash == b.content_hash\n\n    def test_to_row_excludes_raw_includes_key_and_hash(self):\n        row = self._job(raw={\"secret\": 1}).to_row()\n        assert \"raw\" not in row\n        assert row[\"key\"] and row[\"content_hash\"]\n\n    def test_posted_dt_none_when_unparseable(self):\n        assert self._job(posted_at=\"\").posted_dt is None\n```\n\n---\n\n## 2. `filters.py` — pure logic, second-highest ROI\n\n**Untested:** `_compile`, `match`, `filter_jobs` — completely untested including the word-boundary regex behavior.\n\n**Gaps:**\n- Word-boundary matching (`\"go\"` must not match `\"golang\"` inside title, but should match `\"Go Developer\"`)\n- Case-insensitivity\n- `exclude` takes precedence over `include`\n- Empty/`None` `include`/`exclude`/`locations` lists (treated as \"no filter\")\n- Location substring matching (`\"york\"` matches `\"New York\"`)\n- `cutoff`: job with unparseable `posted_at` is **kept**, not dropped (documented behavior, worth locking in)\n- `filter_jobs` `max_age_days` wiring end-to-end, including fractional days\n\n```python\n# tests/test_filters.py\nfrom datetime import datetime, timedelta, timezone\nfrom models import Job\nfrom filters import match, filter_jobs\n\ndef _job(title=\"Software Engineer\", dept=\"\", loc=\"Remote\", posted_at=\"\"):\n    return Job(source=\"greenhouse\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\",\n               title=title, url=\"u\", department=dept, location=loc,\n               posted_at=posted_at)\n\ndef test_include_word_boundary_excludes_substring_match():\n    assert match(_job(title=\"Golang Engineer\"), include=[\"go\"]) is False\n\ndef test_include_matches_whole_word_case_insensitive():\n    assert match(_job(title=\"Go Developer\"), include=[\"GO\"]) is True\n\ndef test_exclude_wins_over_include():\n    j = _job(title=\"Senior Manager\")\n    assert match(j, include=[\"manager\"], exclude=[\"manager\"]) is False\n\ndef test_no_filters_passes_through():\n    assert match(_job()) is True\n\ndef test_location_substring_case_insensitive():\n    assert match(_job(loc=\"New York, NY\"), locations=[\"york\"]) is True\n    assert match(_job(loc=\"Remote\"), locations=[\"york\"]) is False\n\ndef test_cutoff_drops_older_job():\n    old = _job(posted_at=(datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=30)).isoformat())\n    cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=7)\n    assert match(old, cutoff=cutoff) is False\n\ndef test_cutoff_keeps_job_with_unparseable_posted_at():\n    j = _job(posted_at=\"Posted 3 Days Ago\")\n    cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=7)\n    assert match(j, cutoff=cutoff) is True\n\ndef test_filter_jobs_max_age_days_end_to_end():\n    fresh = _job(title=\"Fresh\", posted_at=datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat())\n    stale = _job(title=\"Stale\",\n                 posted_at=(datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=100)).isoformat())\n    out = filter_jobs([fresh, stale], {\"max_age_days\": 10})\n    assert [j.title for j in out] == [\"Fresh\"]\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3. `fetchers.py` — largest file, largest gap (787 lines, 0 tests)\n\nTwo categories: **pure parsers** (test directly, no network) and **fetch_* orchestrators** (test with `respx` mocking `httpx.AsyncClient`).\n\n### 3a. Parsers — no network needed, high value\nUntested: `parse_greenhouse`, `parse_lever`, `_lever_salary`, `parse_ashby`, `_ashby_salary`, `parse_smartrecruiters`, `parse_recruitee`, `parse_workable`, `_extract_ds1`, `_ds1_posted_at`, `parse_google`, `parse_deshaw`, `parse_twosigma`, `parse_optiver`, `parse_meta`, `parse_microsoft`, `parse_netflix`, `_amazon_posted_at`, `parse_amazon`.\n\n**Notable edge cases nobody has verified:**\n- `_lever_salary`: only `min` present without `max` → falls through to `salaryDescriptionPlain`\n- `parse_ashby`: `isListed is False` skip — but what about `isListed` missing entirely (`None`)? Currently NOT skipped (only `is False`) — worth locking in explicitly.\n- `_extract_ds1`: malformed JSON in the regex match → caught, returns `[]`; second regex fallback path is untested\n- `_ds1_posted_at`: index-out-of-range guarded by `len(job) > idx`, but `cell[0]` falsy (`0`) should probably still be skipped — worth testing\n- `parse_deshaw`/`parse_twosigma`: regex-based HTML scraping — dedup via `seen` set, missing optional fields (no href, no location)\n- `_amazon_posted_at`: malformed date string → `\"\"`, not an exception\n- `parse_amazon`/`parse_microsoft`/`parse_netflix`: falsy `id`/timestamp handling\n\n```python\n# tests/test_fetchers_parsers.py\nfrom fetchers import (parse_greenhouse, parse_lever, _lever_salary, parse_ashby,\n                       parse_amazon, _amazon_posted_at, _extract_ds1, parse_google,\n                       parse_deshaw, parse_optiver)\n\ndef test_parse_greenhouse_basic():\n    data = {\"jobs\": [{\"id\": 1, \"title\": \"SWE\", \"absolute_url\": \"u\",\n                       \"location\": {\"name\": \"NYC\"}, \"departments\": [{\"name\": \"Eng\"}],\n                       \"updated_at\": \"2026-01-01\"}]}\n    jobs = parse_greenhouse(\"acme\", data)\n    assert jobs[0].external_id == \"1\"\n    assert jobs[0].department == \"Eng\"\n\ndef test_parse_greenhouse_empty_jobs_list():\n    assert parse_greenhouse(\"acme\", {\"jobs\": []}) == []\n\ndef test_lever_salary_min_max_present():\n    j = {\"salaryRange\": {\"min\": 100000, \"max\": 150000, \"currency\": \"USD\"}}\n    assert _lever_salary(j) == \"USD 100,000–150,000\"\n\ndef test_lever_salary_falls_back_to_description():\n    j = {\"salaryDescriptionPlain\": \"Competitive\"}\n    assert _lever_salary(j) == \"Competitive\"\n\ndef test_lever_salary_missing_returns_empty():\n    assert _lever_salary({}) == \"\"\n\ndef test_parse_ashby_skips_unlisted():\n    data = {\"jobs\": [{\"id\": \"1\", \"isListed\": False, \"title\": \"Hidden\"}]}\n    assert parse_ashby(\"acme\", data) == []\n\ndef test_amazon_posted_at_valid():\n    assert _amazon_posted_at(\"June 26, 2026\") == \"2026-06-26T00:00:00+00:00\"\n\ndef test_amazon_posted_at_malformed_returns_empty():\n    assert _amazon_posted_at(\"not a date\") == \"\"\n\ndef test_extract_ds1_malformed_json_returns_empty_list():\n    html = \"key: 'ds:1', ..., data:[not valid json], sideChannel\"\n    assert _extract_ds1(html) == []\n\ndef test_extract_ds1_no_match_returns_empty_list():\n    assert _extract_ds1(\"<html>nothing here</html>\") == []\n\ndef test_parse_deshaw_dedupes_repeated_job_id():\n    page = ('data-job-id=\"1\"><span class=\"job-display-name\">SWE</span>' * 2)\n    jobs = parse_deshaw(\"deshaw\", page)\n    assert len(jobs) == 1\n\ndef test_parse_optiver_strips_join_us_prefix_for_external_id():\n    items = [{\"title\": \"SWE\", \"href\": \"/join-us/jobs/eng/swe-1\", \"location\": \"AMS\"}]\n    jobs = parse_optiver(\"optiver\", items)\n    assert jobs[0].external_id == \"eng/swe-1\"\n```\n\n### 3b. `_request` retry wrapper — critical untested error-handling path\n**Gaps:** retries on `429/500/502/503/504`, does NOT retry on `404`/other 4xx, exhausts retries and raises `RuntimeError`, exponential backoff bounds. This is the backbone of every network call and has zero coverage.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_fetchers_request.py\nimport httpx, pytest, respx\nfrom fetchers import _request\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_request_retries_on_503_then_succeeds():\n    route = respx.get(\"https://x.test/j\")\n    route.side_effect = [httpx.Response(503), httpx.Response(200, json={\"ok\": True})]\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n        r = await _request(client, \"https://x.test/j\", retries=3)\n    assert r.status_code == 200\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_request_does_not_retry_on_404():\n    respx.get(\"https://x.test/j\").mock(return_value=httpx.Response(404))\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n        with pytest.raises(RuntimeError):\n            await _request(client, \"https://x.test/j\", retries=3)\n    assert respx.calls.call_count == 1  # no retry burned on non-retryable error\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_request_exhausts_retries_and_raises():\n    respx.get(\"https://x.test/j\").mock(return_value=httpx.Response(500))\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n        with pytest.raises(RuntimeError, match=\"failed to fetch\"):\n            await _request(client, \"https://x.test/j\", retries=2)\n```\n*(mark with `@respx.mock` decorator or fixture per respx's API)*\n\n### 3c. Pagination loops (`fetch_twosigma`, `fetch_optiver`, `fetch_workday`, `fetch_google`, `fetch_microsoft`, `fetch_netflix`, `fetch_amazon`) — **entirely untested**\nEach has independent stop conditions (`fresh` empty, `offset >= total`, safety caps like `5000`/`max_pages`). These are exactly where off-by-one bugs live and none are covered.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_fetchers_pagination.py\nimport httpx, respx\nfrom fetchers import fetch_amazon\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\n@respx.mock\nasync def test_fetch_amazon_stops_when_no_fresh_jobs():\n    respx.get(\"https://www.amazon.jobs/en/search.json\").mock(\n        return_value=httpx.Response(200, json={\"jobs\": []}))\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n        jobs = await fetch_amazon(client, {\"company\": \"amazon\"})\n    assert jobs == []\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\n@respx.mock\nasync def test_fetch_amazon_respects_max_pages_cap():\n    # always return one new job -> would loop forever without max_pages\n    call_count = {\"n\": 0}\n    def responder(request):\n        call_count[\"n\"] += 1\n        return httpx.Response(200, json={\"jobs\": [{\"id\": str(call_count[\"n\"]),\n                                                     \"title\": \"SWE\", \"job_path\": \"/x\"}]})\n    respx.get(\"https://www.amazon.jobs/en/search.json\").mock(side_effect=responder)\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n        jobs = await fetch_amazon(client, {\"company\": \"amazon\", \"max_pages\": 3})\n    assert call_count[\"n\"] == 3\n```\n\n### 3d. `fetch_all` — failure isolation, currently unverified\n**Gap:** one source raising must not abort the whole run (`except Exception` swallow-and-log). Also untested: `concurrency` semaphore actually bounds parallelism, and unknown `ats` value raises `ValueError` from `fetch_source`.\n\n```python\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_fetch_all_isolates_source_failures(monkeypatch):\n    async def boom(client, source): raise RuntimeError(\"network down\")\n    async def ok(client, source): return [Job(source=\"x\", company=\"y\",\n                                              external_id=\"1\", title=\"t\", url=\"u\")]\n    monkeypatch.setitem(FETCHERS, \"broken\", boom)\n    monkeypatch.setitem(FETCHERS, \"fine\", ok)\n    jobs = await fetch_all([{\"ats\": \"broken\"}, {\"ats\": \"fine\", \"company\": \"y\"}])\n    assert len(jobs) == 1\n\ndef test_fetch_source_unknown_ats_raises():\n    with pytest.raises(ValueError, match=\"unknown ATS\"):\n        asyncio.run(fetch_source(None, {\"ats\": \"nope\"}))\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. `store.py` — SQLite dedup logic, zero tests, high risk\n\n**Untested:** `Store.__init__`/`_migrate`, `diff` (new/changed/unchanged paths), `_insert`, `_update`, `get_meta`/`set_meta` (including the `ON CONFLICT` upsert), `added_since` (string-comparison ordering claim), `count`, context-manager protocol.\n\n**Gaps:**\n- `diff` returns correct `(new, changed)` split and leaves untouched rows alone (`last_seen` bumps but not `content_hash`)\n- Same job key seen twice in one `diff()` call (in-batch dedup — is it even handled? Looks like it isn't — second occurrence would try `INSERT` after the row already exists from step 1 in-memory query — actually since it queries DB per-job and inserts immediately, a duplicate within the same batch will correctly hit the \"already exists\" branch on its second occurrence. Worth locking in.)\n- `_migrate` adds `salary_range` column to a legacy DB missing it\n- `set_meta` upsert (insert then update same key)\n- `added_since` ordering and strict `>` boundary (not `>=`)\n\n```python\n# tests/test_store.py\nimport pytest\nfrom models import Job\nfrom store import Store\n\n@pytest.fixture\ndef store(tmp_path):\n    with Store(tmp_path / \"test.db\") as s:\n        yield s\n\ndef _job(ext_id=\"1\", title=\"SWE\"):\n    return Job(source=\"greenhouse\", company=\"acme\", external_id=ext_id,\n               title=title, url=\"u\", location=\"NYC\")\n\ndef test_diff_new_job_is_inserted_and_reported_new(store):\n    new, changed = store.diff([_job()])\n    assert len(new) == 1 and changed == []\n    assert store.count() == 1\n\ndef test_diff_unchanged_job_reports_neither(store):\n    store.diff([_job()])\n    new, changed = store.diff([_job()])\n    assert new == [] and changed == []\n\ndef test_diff_changed_content_reports_changed(store):\n    store.diff([_job(title=\"SWE\")])\n    new, changed = store.diff([_job(title=\"Senior SWE\")])\n    assert new == [] and len(changed) == 1\n\ndef test_diff_duplicate_key_within_same_batch(store):\n    j = _job()\n    new, changed = store.diff([j, j])\n    assert store.count() == 1  # second occurrence treated as unchanged, not a crash\n\ndef test_meta_roundtrip_and_upsert(store):\n    assert store.get_meta(\"k\") is None\n    store.set_meta(\"k\", \"v1\")\n    store.set_meta(\"k\", \"v2\")\n    assert store.get_meta(\"k\") == \"v2\"\n\ndef test_added_since_strict_boundary_excludes_equal_timestamp(store):\n    store.diff([_job()])\n    ts = store.conn.execute(\"SELECT first_seen FROM jobs\").fetchone()[0]\n    assert store.added_since(ts) == []  # strictly-after, not >=\n\ndef test_added_since_orders_oldest_first(store):\n    store.diff([_job(\"1\", \"A\")])\n    store.diff([_job(\"2\", \"B\")])\n    rows = store.added_since(\"1970-01-01T00:00:00+00:00\")\n    assert [r[\"external_id\"] for r in rows] == [\"1\", \"2\"]\n\ndef test_migrate_adds_salary_range_to_legacy_schema(tmp_path):\n    import sqlite3\n    path = tmp_path / \"legacy.db\"\n    conn = sqlite3.connect(str(path))\n    conn.execute(\"\"\"CREATE TABLE jobs (key TEXT PRIMARY KEY, source TEXT, company TEXT,\n        external_id TEXT, title TEXT, url TEXT, location TEXT, department TEXT,\n        employment_type TEXT, posted_at TEXT, content_hash TEXT,\n        first_seen TEXT, last_seen TEXT)\"\"\")\n    conn.commit(); conn.close()\n    with Store(path) as s:\n        cols = {r[\"name\"] for r in s.conn.execute(\"PRAGMA table_info(jobs)\")}\n        assert \"salary_range\" in cols\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. `pipeline.py` — orchestration, zero tests\n\n**Untested:** `load_config` (defaults for missing keys), `run` (dry_run vs persisted path), `run_sync`.\n\n**Gaps:**\n- `load_config` default-filling for every optional key (`sources`, `filters`, `db`, `concurrency`)\n- `dry_run=True` must NOT touch the store or call `dispatch` — currently unverified\n- Return dict shape (`matched`/`new`/`changed`) for both branches\n\n```python\n# tests/test_pipeline.py\nimport pytest, yaml\nfrom pipeline import load_config, run\n\ndef test_load_config_fills_defaults(tmp_path):\n    p = tmp_path / \"c.yaml\"\n    p.write_text(yaml.dump({}))\n    cfg = load_config(p)\n    assert cfg == {\"sources\": [], \"filters\": {}, \"db\": \"jobs.db\", \"concurrency\": 8}\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_run_dry_run_does_not_persist(tmp_path, monkeypatch):\n    cfg_path = tmp_path / \"c.yaml\"\n    cfg_path.write_text(yaml.dump({\"sources\": [], \"db\": str(tmp_path / \"jobs.db\")}))\n    result = await run(cfg_path, dry_run=True)\n    assert result == {\"matched\": 0, \"new\": 0, \"changed\": 0}\n    assert not (tmp_path / \"jobs.db\").exists()  # store never opened\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_run_persists_and_dispatches(tmp_path, monkeypatch):\n    import pipeline\n    async def fake_fetch_all(sources, concurrency): \n        from models import Job\n        return [Job(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"t\", url=\"u\")]\n    dispatched = {}\n    monkeypatch.setattr(pipeline, \"fetch_all\", fake_fetch_all)\n    monkeypatch.setattr(pipeline, \"dispatch\", lambda new, changed: dispatched.update(new=new))\n\n    cfg_path = tmp_path / \"c.yaml\"\n    cfg_path.write_text(yaml.dump({\"sources\": [{}], \"db\": str(tmp_path / \"jobs.db\")}))\n    result = await run(cfg_path, dry_run=False)\n    assert result[\"new\"] == 1\n    assert len(dispatched[\"new\"]) == 1\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. `notify.py` — every notifier untested, including error isolation\n\n**Untested:** `_line`, `notify_console`, `notify_slack`, `notify_webhook`, `notify_email`, `_sms_body`, `notify_sms`, `dispatch`.\n\n**Gaps:**\n- Every notifier's **env-var gate**: missing var(s) → silent no-op, no network call\n- Every notifier's **empty new/changed gate**: configured but nothing to send → no-op\n- `notify_sms`/`notify_slack`/`notify_webhook`: actual payload shape sent (mock `httpx.post`)\n- `notify_sms.raise_for_status()` on Twilio failure — is this caught by `dispatch`'s try/except? (yes, but untested)\n- **`dispatch` error isolation** — the most important integration-style gap: one notifier raising must not block the others.\n- `_sms_body` truncation at `limit` (`+N more` line)\n\n```python\n# tests/test_notify.py\nimport httpx, pytest\nfrom models import Job\nfrom notify import notify_slack, notify_sms, _sms_body, dispatch\n\ndef _job(title=\"SWE\"):\n    return Job(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=title, url=\"u\")\n\ndef test_notify_slack_noop_when_env_var_missing(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.delenv(\"SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL\", raising=False)\n    called = []\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"httpx.post\", lambda *a, **k: called.append(1))\n    notify_slack([_job()], [])\n    assert called == []\n\ndef test_notify_slack_noop_when_no_jobs(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.setenv(\"SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL\", \"https://hooks.example/x\")\n    called = []\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"httpx.post\", lambda *a, **k: called.append(1))\n    notify_slack([], [])\n    assert called == []\n\ndef test_notify_slack_posts_when_configured_and_new(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.setenv(\"SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL\", \"https://hooks.example/x\")\n    calls = {}\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"httpx.post\", lambda url, json, timeout: calls.update(url=url, json=json))\n    notify_slack([_job(\"SWE\")], [])\n    assert \"SWE\" in calls[\"json\"][\"text\"]\n\ndef test_sms_body_truncates_over_limit():\n    jobs = [_job(f\"Job {i}\") for i in range(10)]\n    body = _sms_body(jobs, [], limit=8)\n    assert \"+2 more\" in body\n\ndef test_notify_sms_raises_on_twilio_failure(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.setenv(\"TWILIO_ACCOUNT_SID\", \"sid\")\n    monkeypatch.setenv(\"TWILIO_AUTH_TOKEN\", \"tok\")\n    monkeypatch.setenv(\"TWILIO_FROM\", \"+1\")\n    monkeypatch.setenv(\"TWILIO_TO\", \"+2\")\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"httpx.post\", lambda *a, **k: httpx.Response(400, request=httpx.Request(\"POST\", \"https://x\")))\n    with pytest.raises(httpx.HTTPStatusError):\n        notify_sms([_job()], [])\n\ndef test_dispatch_isolates_notifier_failures(monkeypatch, capsys):\n    import notify\n    def boom(new, changed): raise RuntimeError(\"smtp down\")\n    monkeypatch.setattr(notify, \"NOTIFIERS\", [boom, notify.notify_console])\n    dispatch([], [])  # must not raise\n    assert \"failed\" in capsys.readouterr().out\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7. `agent.py` — deterministic helpers untested (LLM launch path is out of scope for unit tests)\n\n**Untested (and testable without touching Claude/network):** `cmd_db_new` (watermark truncation-at-group-boundary logic), `cmd_db_mark` (ISO validation, `--now`, neither-arg error), `_normalize_ats` (ATS character rules, must skip `<style>`/`<script>` blocks and tag attributes), `_chrome_bin` discovery order, argv parsing in `main()` (mode-word vs flag split).\n\n**Gaps — the trickiest one nobody has verified:**\n- `cmd_db_new`'s truncation logic: \"truncate only at `first_seen` group boundaries\" — this is exactly the kind of off-by-one that needs a test with >`limit` rows spanning 3 timestamp groups.\n- `_normalize_ats` must NOT rewrite characters inside `<style>`/`<script>` or inside tag attributes, only body text.\n- `cmd_db_mark` rejects a non-ISO watermark with exit code `2` and doesn't write to the store.\n- `main()`'s flag/mode-word split (`words[:i]` vs `words[i:]` at first `-`-prefixed token).\n\n```python\n# tests/test_agent.py\nimport pytest\nfrom agent import _normalize_ats, cmd_db_mark\nfrom store import Store\n\ndef test_normalize_ats_replaces_em_dash_in_body():\n    html, counts = _normalize_ats(\"<p>foo\\u2014bar</p>\")\n    assert \"foo-bar\" in html\n    assert counts[\"em-dash\"] == 1\n\ndef test_normalize_ats_skips_style_block():\n    html, counts = _normalize_ats(\"<style>content: '\\u2014';</style><p>ok</p>\")\n    assert \"\\u2014\" in html  # untouched inside <style>\n    assert \"em-dash\" not in counts\n\ndef test_normalize_ats_skips_tag_attributes():\n    html, counts = _normalize_ats('<a title=\"foo\\u2014bar\">x</a>')\n    assert \"foo\\u2014bar\" in html  # attribute untouched\n    assert \"em-dash\" not in counts\n\ndef test_db_mark_rejects_invalid_iso(tmp_path, capsys):\n    cfg = tmp_path / \"c.yaml\"\n    cfg.write_text(f\"db: {tmp_path / 'jobs.db'}\\n\")\n    rc = cmd_db_mark([\"not-a-date\", \"-c\", str(cfg)])\n    assert rc == 2\n\ndef test_db_mark_requires_watermark_or_now(tmp_path):\n    cfg = tmp_path / \"c.yaml\"\n    cfg.write_text(f\"db: {tmp_path / 'jobs.db'}\\n\")\n    assert cmd_db_mark([\"-c\", str(cfg)]) == 2\n\ndef test_db_new_truncates_at_group_boundary(tmp_path, monkeypatch, capsys):\n    # seed store with 3 first_seen groups of 2 rows each, limit=3\n    # expect only the first *complete* group (2 rows) kept, truncated=True\n    ...  # build via Store.diff() across 3 separate calls w/ frozen/advancing clock\n```\n\n---\n\n## 8. Integration test gaps (no fetcher currently touches `filters`→`store`→`notify` together)\n\nNone of the modules are exercised end-to-end except manually. Add one seam-level test:\n\n```python\n# tests/test_integration_pipeline.py\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_pipeline_end_to_end_with_fake_fetcher(tmp_path, monkeypatch):\n    \"\"\"fetch_all (stubbed) -> filter_jobs -> Store.diff -> dispatch (stubbed),\n    run twice: 1st run reports jobs as new, 2nd identical run reports none.\"\"\"\n```\nThis is the single highest-value integration test to add first — it would have caught real bugs in the dedup/filter boundary (e.g. the `cutoff`-keeps-unparseable-dates behavior interacting with a job that's actually stale but has a bad timestamp).\n\n---\n\n## Priority ranking\n\n| Priority | Module | Why |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1 | `models.py`, `filters.py` | Pure functions, zero mocking, highest bug-catch/effort ratio |\n| 2 | `store.py` | Dedup correctness is the whole point of the app; sqlite is trivial to test with `tmp_path` |\n| 3 | `fetchers.py` parsers | 19 parser functions, each a silent-failure risk (defensive `.get()` chains hide schema drift) |\n| 4 | `fetchers.py` `_request`/pagination/`fetch_all` | Network-adjacent logic (retry, backoff, failure isolation) — needs `respx` |\n| 5 | `notify.py` | Straightforward env-gated no-ops, but `dispatch`'s failure isolation is worth locking in |\n| 6 | `pipeline.py`, `agent.py` db helpers | Thin orchestration, but `cmd_db_new`'s watermark-truncation logic is genuinely subtle |\n| 7 | `agent.py` `run_claude`/`main` launcher, `cli.py` | Mostly argv wiring / subprocess exec — lowest value, can stay manually verified |\n",
